{
  "task_summary": "Remove duplicate integers from a list while preserving first occurrence order.",
  "approach": "To remove duplicate integers from a list while preserving first occurrence order, we can use a dictionary to track the indices of each unique integer as we iterate through the list. When we encounter a new integer, we add it to the dictionary with its index. If the integer is already present in the dictionary, we ignore it and move on to the next element.",
  "code": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\ndef remove_duplicate_integers(nums: List[int]) -> List[int]:\n    indices = {}\n    result = []\n\n    for i, num in enumerate(nums):\n        if num not in indices:\n            indices[num] = i\n            result.append(num)\n\n    return result\n```",
  "complexity": {
    "time": "O(n)",
    "space": "O(n)"
  },
  "edge_cases": [
    "If the input list is empty, an empty list should be returned.",
